      "targeted_response_start_logprob": 0.0
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Blueberries can be quite finicky, but don't worry, I'm here to help. The pH level of your soil can indeed affect the availability of nutrients, including iron, to your blueberries. When the pH is too high (alkaline), it can lead to iron deficiency, as the soil's pH can cause iron to precipitate out of the soil and become less available to the plants. On the other hand, if the pH is too low (acidic), it can also cause problems, as some nutrients like iron can become too available, leading to nutrient imbalances. A slightly acidic to neutral pH (around 4.0-5.5) is generally ideal for blueberries.",
      "source": "target",
